{
  "text": "The latter implies that k(t) * = k(\u2212t) on [\u2212T, T], and hence k is a hermitian kernel. Under certain minimality conditions the converse statement is also true. More precisely, if k given by (6.1) with the pair (A, B) being controllable and the pair (C, A) being observable, then k(t) * = k(\u2212t) implies that there exists a unique invertible hermitian matrix H such that (6.2) holds. Let \u03c4 \u2208 (0, T]. As proved in [CITATION_1] ",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "118071972"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "118071972": {
      "title": "On inversion of convolution integral operators on a finite interval",
      "abstract": "The Gohberg-Heinig inversion formula for convolution operators on a finite interval is computed explicitly for the case when the kernel function is given by k(t)=Ce tA B, whereA,B, and C are matrices of appropriate sizes."
    }
  }
}